sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Qakbot Rundll32 Fake DLL Extension Execution
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects specific process tree behavior of a "rundll32" execution where the DLL doesn't have the ".dll" extension. This is often linked with potential Qakbot activity.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Pikabot Fake DLL Extension Execution Via Rundll32.EXE
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects specific process tree behavior linked to "rundll32" executions, wherein the associated DLL lacks a common ".dll" extension, often signaling potential Pikabot activity.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Windows Shell/Scripting Application File Write to Suspicious Folder
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects Windows shells and scripting applications that write files to suspicious folders

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: File Decoded From Base64/Hex Via Certutil.EXE
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the execution of certutil with either the "decode" or "decodehex" flags to decode base64 or hex encoded files. This can be abused by attackers to decode an encoded payload before execution
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Jonhnathan Ribeiro, oscd.community

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects a suspicious process spawning from one of the Microsoft Office suite products (Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Publisher, Visio, etc.)
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Markus Neis, FPT.EagleEye Team, Vadim Khrykov, Cyb3rEng, Michael Haag, Christopher Peacock @securepeacock, @scythe_io

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects a rundll32 that communicates with public IP addresses

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Unsigned DLL Loaded by Windows Utility
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects windows utilities loading an unsigned or untrusted DLL.
Adversaries often abuse those programs to proxy execution of malicious code.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: DLL Load By System Process From Suspicious Locations
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects when a system process (i.e. located in system32, syswow64, etc.) loads a DLL from a suspicious location or a location with permissive permissions such as "C:\Users\Public"

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Office Application Initiated Network Connection To Non-Local IP
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects an office application (Word, Excel, PowerPoint)  that initiate a network connection to a non-private IP addresses.
This rule aims to detect traffic similar to one seen exploited in CVE-2021-42292.
This rule will require an initial baseline and tuning that is specific to your organization.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Christopher Peacock '@securepeacock', SCYTHE '@scythe_io', Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Rundll32 Execution With Uncommon DLL Extension
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the execution of rundll32 with a command line that doesn't contain a common extension
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Tim Shelton, Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Yassine Oukessou

mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may use rootkits to hide the presence of programs, files, network connections, services, drivers, and other system components.
Adversaries may use bootkits to persist on systems.
Adversaries may attempt to hide artifacts associated with their behaviors to evade detection.
Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters.
Adversaries may use [Obfuscated Files or Information](https://attack.
Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools.
Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.
Adversaries may circumvent mechanisms designed to control elevate privileges to gain higher-level permissions.
Adversaries may abuse Pre-OS Boot mechanisms as a way to establish persistence on a system.
Adversaries may undermine security controls that will either warn users of untrusted activity or prevent execution of untrusted programs.
Adversaries may install a root certificate on a compromised system to avoid warnings when connecting to adversary controlled web servers.
Adversaries may use hidden windows to conceal malicious activity from the plain sight of users.
Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts.
Adversaries may set files and directories to be hidden to evade detection mechanisms.
An adversary may attempt to get detailed information about the operating system and hardware, including version, patches, hotfixes, service packs, and architecture.
Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to gather information about the system, configuration, and installed software.
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment.
Adversaries may leverage the resources of co-opted systems in order to solve resource intensive problems, which may impact system and/or hosted service availability.
